@node Text operations
@section Text operations

@findex pdf-tools-extras-count-words
When you need a quick word count for a PDF, the command @code{pdf-tools-extras-count-words} extracts the text with the external @samp{pdftotext} utility, pipes it through @samp{wc -w}, copies the result to the kill ring, and displays it in the echo area. This is handy for checking the length of a paper or report without leaving Emacs.

@findex pdf-tools-extras-copy-dwim
The command @code{pdf-tools-extras-copy-dwim} copies PDF text to the kill ring with do-what-I-mean behavior. If a region is active (selected with the mouse or keyboard in the PDF view), it copies only the selected text via @code{pdf-view-kill-ring-save}. If no region is active, it extracts the entire document text using @code{pdf-tools-extras-convert-pdf}, joins lines that were broken mid-sentence, and copies the result. A message confirms that the full text was copied.

@findex pdf-annot-extras-add-highlight-markup-annotation
Highlighting a passage in a PDF and then separately copying the text is a two-step operation in vanilla @samp{pdf-tools}. The command @code{pdf-annot-extras-add-highlight-markup-annotation} combines both steps: it creates a highlight annotation on the active region and simultaneously copies the highlighted text to the kill ring. It accepts optional COLOR and PROPERTY-ALIST arguments, just like the underlying @code{pdf-annot-add-markup-annotation}.

@node External interaction
@section External interaction

@findex pdf-tools-extras-open-externally
Sometimes you need to view a PDF in a dedicated external application, for example to use features not available in Emacs. The command @code{pdf-tools-extras-open-externally} opens the current PDF in the system's default viewer. On macOS, if the @samp{opentopage} script is installed in @samp{~/bin}, the PDF opens at the current page. Otherwise it falls back to a plain @samp{open} command.

@findex pdf-tools-extras-toggle-writeroom
For distraction-free reading, @code{pdf-tools-extras-toggle-writeroom} toggles @samp{writeroom-mode} with a fixed width of 120 columns and then calls @code{pdf-view-fit-height-to-window} to adjust the PDF display. This provides a clean reading environment without the need to manually configure @samp{writeroom-mode} settings.

@findex pdf-tools-extras-delete
The command @code{pdf-tools-extras-delete} permanently deletes the PDF file underlying the current buffer. It asks for confirmation with @code{yes-or-no-p} before proceeding. If confirmed, it deletes the file and kills the buffer. Use this when triaging downloaded papers that you do not wish to keep.

@node Ebib integration
@section Ebib integration

@findex pdf-tools-extras-open-in-ebib
If your PDF files are named after Bib@TeX{} keys (e.g., @samp{Smith2023.pdf} corresponds to the key @samp{Smith2023}), the command @code{pdf-tools-extras-open-in-ebib} extracts the base name of the current PDF and calls @code{ebib-extras-open-key} to jump to that entry in @samp{ebib}. It signals an error if the current buffer is not in @code{pdf-view-mode}. See @samp{ebib-extras.el} for the entry-opening logic.

